title: SFH on avian influenza and Middle East Respiratory Syndrome
content_text:
p>
	Following is the transcript of remarks made by the Secretary for Food and 
	Health, Dr Ko Wing-man, when meeting the media at the lobby of West Wing, 
	Central Government Offices, today (June 12): Secretary for Food and Health: Given that no new case of (Avian Influenza A) 
	H7N9 has been detected in Hong Kong in the past two months and the risk of 
	the spread of the disease in the region has reduced, we have decided to 
	lower the influenza response level under the Framework of Government's

lower the influenza response level under the Framework of Government's 
	Preparedness Plan for Influenza Pandemic from "Serious" to "Alert". The Government, however, will continue to keep a close watch on the 
	situation and maintain tight contact with the World Health Organization with 
	a view to updating our overall outbreak management plan whenever 
	appropriate. Based on the latest risk assessment, the Hospital Authority and the 
	Department of Health have also adjusted their clinical and infection control 
	measures including the duration of quarantine period, the introduction of

measures including the duration of quarantine period, the introduction of 
	more ECMO (extracorporeal membrane oxygenation) machines in public hospitals 
	and the improvement of facilities in the quarantine camp. As for the MERS, or Middle East Respiratory Syndrome, the Centre for Health 
	Protection has formulated the Preparedness Plan for MERS to strengthen our 
	response capacity for the disease. Regarding the resumption of live poultry imports from the Mainland, we have 
	all along been maintaining a very close dialogue with our Mainland

all along been maintaining a very close dialogue with our Mainland 
	counterparts with a view to working out the necessary arrangements. We will 
	make public announcement when the date of resumption is fixed. Reporter: Do you expect the summer heat to facilitate the spread of the 
	MERS? Secretary for Food and Health: Up to this particular moment, I am not aware 
	of any research or study pointing to the fact that the summer heat might 
	aggravate the situation in terms of MERS transmission. (Please also refer to the
aggravate the situation in terms of MERS transmission. (Please also refer to the Chinese portion of the transcript.)
